vectorData.altText: You will find the parotid duct about a finger’s breadth inferior to the zygomatic arch, and running roughly parallel to it. It is a little thinner than a pencil.
Your first task will be to identify the parotid duct (A) and branches of the facial nerve (B) superficial to the masseter muscle (C)     .

Clean it by blunt dissection, moving your instruments parallel to the duct and adjacent branches of the facial nerve. This way, you are less likely to sever them. 
You may encounter and clean a few branches of the facial nerve as you work, but do not try to complete a full dissection of the branches of the facial nerve. 
An exceptional dissection demonstrating all motor branches of the facial nerve is available in Grant’s Museum and is part of your Field Trip.

The Masseter and Temporalis Muscles
The fibres of the masseter muscle pass from the zygomatic arch to the angle of the mandible and functions to elevate the mandible (A).

The temporalis muscle has a wide attachment to the side of the skull from which the fibres converge as a tendinous attachment to the coronoid process of the mandible (B). It is a powerful elevator of the mandible (C), and also retracts the mandible via contraction of its posterior fibres (D).
The masseter and temporalis, along with the medial and lateral pterygoid muscles (Ex. 4.3), are the muscles of mastication. They are innervated by the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve, V3.
